.TH _PRINTF 3 "01-10-2025" "1.0" "Holberton School"
.SH NAME
_printf \- formatted output to stdout (supports %c, %s, %%, %d, %i)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.br
.B int _printf(const char *format, ...);
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf
function produces output according to a format string.

Supported conversion specifiers:
.TP
.B %c
Print a single character.
.TP
.B %s
Print a string. If the argument is NULL, prints "(null)".
.TP
.B %%
Print a literal percent sign.
.TP
.B %d, %i
Print a signed decimal integer.

The function uses only the
.B write(2)
system call to output characters. No other C library buffering functions are used.

.LP
If
.B format
is NULL, the function returns -1.
If a lone '%' appears at the end of the string or an unknown specifier is used, it prints '%' followed by the unknown character.
.SH RETURN VALUE
The function returns the number of characters printed (excluding the final null byte) or -1 on error.
.SH EXAMPLES
.EX
_printf("Hello %s %c %%\n", "World", '!'); 
# Output: Hello World ! %
_printf("Number: %d, Another: %i\n", 123, -456); 
# Output: Number: 123, Another: -456
.EE
.SH NOTES
This function is a simplified re-implementation of the standard printf, intended for educational purposes and Holberton School projects.
